Elon Musk's X & xAI sue Apple & Open AI: What happens next?
content.description:
X (formerly Twitter) and xAI (XAAI.PVT), owned by Tesla (TSLA) CEO Elon Musk, are suing Apple (AAPL) and OpenAI (OPAI.PVT). Musk's companies allege that Apple and OpenAI's partnership is anti-competitive and that the government should intervene due to antitrust laws.

Yahoo Finance Senior Legal Reporter Alexis Keenan outlines the details of the suit.

content.title: Inside Elon Musk's suit against Apple and OpenAI: 'This is a tale of two monopolists'
content.summary: Elon Musk followed through on Monday with a warning to sue Apple and OpenAI over their agreement to integrate OpenAI’s chatbot into Apple’s operating systems and prioritize the chatbot in its app store.

content.title: Apple’s Annual Event Will Be Sept 9. What to Expect for the iPhone and AI.
content.summary: Apple  will host its annual product event on Sept. 9, the company said Tuesday.  Investors and customers alike will be looking for announcements regarding the company’s next iPhone launch and artificial intelligence updates.  The  Apple  event—almost always takes place in September—unveils what new products and updates the company will be launching in the weeks to follow.

content.title: Apple to hold fall event on September 9, new iPhones expected
content.summary: The event will be held at the Steve Jobs Theater at Apple's headquarters in Cupertino, California and serve as a showcase of the company's efforts to integrate artificial intelligence into its devices.  Media reports have said Apple will also unveil a slimmer version of its latest iPhone, possibly branded as the iPhone Air, echoing its iPad Air and MacBook Air lines.  The company is also expected to showcase new entry-level, high-end Apple Watches, upgraded iPad Pros and a faster version of the Vision Pro headset, Bloomberg News has reported recently.

content.title: Trump Takes Aim at Digital Taxes. What It Means for Tech Stocks.
content.summary: President Donald Trump is threatening to penalize countries that impose digital taxes and regulation on major technology companies.  “I put all Countries with Digital Taxes, Legislation, Rules, or Regulations, on notice that unless these discriminatory actions are removed, I, as President of the United States, will impose substantial additional Tariffs on that Country’s Exports to the U.S.A., and institute Export restrictions on our Highly Protected Technology and Chips,” Trump wrote in a post on his Truth Social platform on Monday evening.  Digital taxes are placed on certain revenue streams generated by online platforms and apps.
